23. belli...domique: the rhythm of the line is certainly in favour of the interpretation, which connects these words with placuisse rather than with primis. But is it possible to suppose that Horace should have ventured to assert that his military exploits won him favour with the primi urbis, even admitting that he would have placed Brutus and Cassius in this position? We need not take his hurnorous phrase in Carni. 11. 7, 10 relicta non bene parmula as a seriously intended confession of cowardice; but neither is there any reason to suppose that he particularly distinguished himself. Besides Augustus, Pollio, Munatius Plancus, Messala and others were distinguished in war as well as in peace.
